      "shell": "Maple or birch wood-shell construction",
      "description": "The snare voice on \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" is the percussive signature of the record. In a mix that pushes the down-tuned guitars and bass into the entire low-mid range, the snare had to claim its space through sheer brightness and cut — and a 14\" x 5.5\" wood-shell snare delivers exactly that profile: enough body to feel substantial, but enough top-end attack to slice through the wall of Tampa guitar tone.\n\nWood shells (maple, birch, or hybrid constructions) give the snare a warmer, more musical voice than the bright, almost metallic crack of steel shells. For Mazurkiewicz's playing on \"Tomb of the Mutilated,\" that wood character serves the album well — the snare punches without becoming so brittle that it competes with the guitars in the high-mids. Across \"Hammer Smashed Face,\" the snare's backbeat anchors the iconic mid-tempo groove that made the song so recognizable; across the blast passages of \"I Cum Blood\" and \"Beyond the Cemetery,\" the snare articulates each rapid single-stroke distinctly even at speeds that would blur lesser instruments together.\n\nThe 5.5\" depth keeps the response fast. Deeper snares (6.5\" and up) sustain longer and feel heavier, but they give up some of the rapid-response speed that blast beat playing demands. The 5.5\" dimension is the death metal sweet spot: enough body to project, fast enough to articulate at velocity.\n\nScott Burns close-miked the snare with the Shure SM57 he used on virtually every Morrisound session, positioned tight to the head for maximum direct sound and minimal cymbal bleed. Burns kept the snare prominent in the final mix — a calculated choice that lets the listener track Mazurkiewicz's playing through the dense guitar arrangements that drove the record.",
