      "title": "Scott Burns at Morrisound: The 1992 Drum Capture",
      "content": "By the time Cannibal Corpse arrived at Morrisound Studios in 1992 to track \"Tomb of the Mutilated,\" Scott Burns had already engineered or co-produced more landmark death metal albums than anyone else on Earth. He had spent the previous three years refining a drum-recording philosophy specifically designed for extreme metal, and the techniques he applied to Mazurkiewicz's kit on \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" were the mature version of methods he had been developing since \"Altars of Madness.\"\n\n**The Morrisound Philosophy:**\nBurns rejected the standard rock-recording assumption that drums needed room ambience to feel large. For extreme metal, the opposite was true: room sound at extreme tempos blurred into wash, kicks lost articulation, and the entire kit collapsed into noise. Burns treated the Morrisound tracking room to minimize reflections, close-miked every drum, and let the drum sound be defined by direct attack rather than acoustic environment.\n\n**Microphone Setup:**\n- Kick drums: AKG D112 inside each drum, positioned for maximum beater attack\n- Snare: Shure SM57 close-miked on top, with minimal bottom-mic bleed\n- Toms: Sennheiser MD421 on each, tight to the head\n- Hi-hat: AKG C451, angled to reject cymbal wash\n- Overheads: AKG C414s in tight XY for cymbal capture with minimal room contribution\n- Room mics: Minimal or none — the treated room contributed almost nothing\n\n**No Triggers, Pure Performance:**\nLike \"Altars of Madness\" before it, \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" was tracked with pure acoustic drums. There were no triggers reinforcing the kicks, no samples blended into the snare. Mazurkiewicz's consistency — already a hallmark of his playing by 1992 — was good enough that Burns could capture the performance straight and trust it to translate.\n\n**The 1992 Refinement:**\nBy the time of the \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" sessions, Burns had introduced subtle refinements over the dry, aggressive template of his earliest death metal work. The kick had slightly more low-end weight, the snare carried a touch more body, and the overall mix had matured into something that felt heavy and brutal without being clinical. The Cannibal Corpse identity — slightly more low-mid presence than Morbid Angel, a touch more snare bite than Death — emerged from these subtle production choices.\n\n**The Mix Approach:**\nBurns positioned the drums forward and dry in the final mix. Mazurkiewicz's playing had to remain readable through three guitars (Bob Rusay and Jack Owen) and Alex Webster's bass, and that clarity was a production priority. The drum mix never sits behind the guitars — it locks with them at parity, defining the rhythmic backbone of every track.\n\n**The Legacy of This Capture:**\n\"Tomb of the Mutilated\" is one of the cleanest, most readable death metal drum performances ever captured. Three decades later, drummers studying Mazurkiewicz's playing on this album can hear every kick stroke, every snare ghost, every cymbal accent. That clarity is Burns's contribution — and it's the reason \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" remains a tracking-clinic reference for the genre.",
